4.51/5  rDev +0.2%look: 4.25 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.25 |  overall: 4.75Markyg21, May 02, 2017
2.9/5  rDev -35.6%look: 2.5 | smell: 3 | taste: 3 | feel: 2.75 |  overall: 2.75Serving: Can
Canned: Mar-17-2017 (Consumed April 30)
A:
Pours a bright orange with a gross, scummy head that looks like literal dirty soap foam.  No retention; no lacing. (2.5)
S:
Sunny Delight and pez, lemon-pine cleaner. (3)
T:
Unfortunately this one follows the nose. Candied oranges, lysol, some doughy malt, rum. (3)
M:
Sticky body with active carbonation and a lingering acrid finish. (2.75)
O:
I do not like this one at all, unfortunately.  I feel bad even writing that, but I don't know what to say.  
I don't think anything is wrong with it as far as off-flavors, infection, etc. but good god is it ever all over the place. It is hideous to start with.  I realize some people don't care about this, but it didn't make a good first impression. There is some really clean artificial orange smell at the beginning but as it warms it becomes increasingly malt- and booze-heavy. It is acrid and has a weird artificial candy/cleaner taste to it that is both intriguing and off-putting, bitter and sweet, dry and sticky. It is not pleasant to drink, I could really taste/feel the alcohol as well. 
Now for my splainin' and justification.  Reading about what it's made with leads me to the conclusion that with as many random hops as they used it is inevitable that they all change in different ways and at different rates. Eventually it's bound to be a mess.  This was a mess. Now, I will admit that this can was past the ideal shelf life for this type of beers (if barely), but I am confident that it was stored/transported properly, it has a lot of booze and they are a huge god damned brewery.  If your beer is undrinkable after a few weeks, there might be a problem with said beer in my humble opinion.
Is it a little long in the tooth?  Maybe.  Have I had many, many beers (even from these guys) that are just as old but weren't this weird?  Absolutely.  Was I having an off day?  Perhaps, but after I dumped what I couldn't finish of this monstrosity I cleansed the palate with an older (by over a month) IPA from a no-name brewery and it was excellent.  Anyway, Sometimes subtlety is a beautiful thing.  At the very least I can now say I have given the lowest (or one of the lowest) rating to one of the highest rated beers.  Honestly this tastes like a Trillium barleywine or something. I wouldn't have this one again, though if I was there and it was fresh on tap you better believe I'd try it just to be sure it wasn't a fluke. (2.75)
All that said, happy belated birthday, Trillium, you make some incredible beers! 2,536 charactersTheDoctor, May 02, 2017
