4.25/5  rDev -5.6%look: 3.25 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.25 | feel: 4.25 |  overall: 4.25Drank from a 1 pint can purchased at Trillium Brewing Company, Canton, MA
03/17/17
Served in a snifter
Review #1350
Cloudy, dull yellow ochre appearance. Surprisingly translucent by Trillium standards. The body was capped by a fleeting film of fizzy white bubbles. No head or lacing whatsoever.
Really bright, punchy aroma. Super hoppy and fruity. Somewhat sweet. Overripe peach initially came through strong. Lots of citrus too. Orange peel was most noticeable. Zesty lime notes were also apparent. There was a dank hoppy note as well. As the beer sat, the sweetness came forth. I also picked up a bit of crisp white winey-ness.
‪The flavor was hoppy and fruity as well but also sweeter than I anticipated. Bready malts and juicy orange notes combined nicely on the front end. Fairly sweet. Some tangerine as well. Slightly tart and tangy. Zesty lemon and lime notes came through in the center. More orange and orange rind on the back end and the finish. White grapefruit notes lingered after the swallow. Hint of pithy bitterness. For a 10% ABV beer, the booze was well masked but became more noticeable by the drink's end.
Nice creamy, frothy mouthfeel. Medium bodied for the style. Slightly syrupy. The liquid contained a fine, zippy effervescence.
I am typically a huge fan of Trillium's hoppy beers, but this anniversary triple IPA was sweeter and had a more "muddled" hop profile than I am accustomed to. All in all, still a terrific beer but perhaps a bit disappointing given the hype surrounding it. 1,516 charactersDamian, Mar 21, 2017
