4.32/5  rDev -4%look: 4.5 | smell: 4.25 | taste: 4.25 | feel: 4.25 |  overall: 4.5blisscent, Mar 20, 2017
4.53/5  rDev +0.7%look: 4.5 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.25 |  overall: 4.75Canned: 3/17/17
Reviewed: 3/19/17 and again 4/2/17 with indicated modifications.
Poured into Trillium tulip glass.
Drank chilled, not cold.
A: Pours a very turbid dark orange color. Rocky, larger bubbles in the half finger of off-white head that doesn't last long.
S: Smells strongly of orange, orange rind, citrus. Underlying smell of papaya, mangoes. A bit of a resinous character.
T: Citrus, orange, and papayas dominate. Can taste the vinous, white wine character from the Nelson. After two weeks, booze is next to undetectable and the beer is fairly smooth. Some prickling in the mouth, but not unpleasant.
F: Medium, medium-minus mouth feel. It's not quite what some other Trillium beers are, but you can only fit so much grain into one batch when trying to get enough fermentable sugars to get to 10%. Carbonation is medium, medium-high which is a fair choice given the slightly thinner mouth feel. After two weeks, no warming from booze.
O: Definitely up there in the TIPA category. After letting the beer clean up a bit, it is much cleaner in flavor and the nuances are much more detectable. It's juicy and easy to drink. Won't be pounding these at 10%, but I will enjoy the last one I have. 1,205 charactersSpoild, Mar 20, 2017
